  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT307-kilavi">piriviṭaik kaṭuñcol colliya tōḻikkuk kiḻatti colliyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER to the confidante who spoke harsh words in
          the time of separation. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT307">
          <l> vaḷaiyuṭait taṉaiya tākip palartoḻac</l>
          <l> cevvāy vāṉat taiyeṉat tōṉṟi</l>
          <l> yiṉṉam piṟantaṉṟu piṟaiyē yaṉṉō</l>
          <l> maṟantaṉar kollō tāmē kaḷiṟutaṉ</l>
          <l> ṉuyaṅkunaṭai maṭappiṭi varutta nōṉātu</l>
          <l> nilaiyuyar yāan tolaiyak kutti</l>
          <l> veṇṇār koṇṭu kaicuvait taṇṇān</l>
          <l> taḻuṅka ṉeñcamoṭu muḻaṅku</l>
          <l> matta nīḷiṭai yaḻappirin tōrē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent4">Just as a broken bangle, for many to worship,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">appearing, wonderfully, <note place="foot"> I do not take <term xml:lang="ta"> aiyeṉa </term> as an ideophone here, but as a adverbial formation of the type <term xml:lang="ta"> teṟṟeṉa </term>. Thus probably too T.V.G., who explains it to mean either "wonderfully" or "speedily".    </note> in the red mouth, the sky,</l>
          <l>now also the crescent moon has been born. <note place="foot"> T.V.G. explains the presence of the crescent moon in this poem as an allusion to a later poetic and poetological topos, namely that the new moon would be worshipped by virgins, so that the confidante by HER not worshipping it any longer is able to deduce the fact that she has had connection with a man. The point of this poem then might be that, instead of worshipping (along with the confidante?) the new moon just arising, SHE begins to talk of her man. Apart from the poetological unlikeliness of such a way of revelation (<term xml:lang="ta"> pālai </term> poems are supposed to belong to the <term xml:lang="ta"> kaṟpu </term> stage), also the wording does not exactly encourage such a reading. The forthcoming moon might only be meant as a signal of the evening, the long and lonely time for sad musings on the whereabouts of the beloved.     </note> Alas!</l>
          <l>Has he forgotten, he,</l>
          <l>who separated, so that [I] cry, for the long way on the road,</l>
          <l rend="indent">where the elephant bull is thundering, with an afflicted heart,</l>
          <l rend="indent">not enduring the suffering of his youthful female</l>
          <l rend="indent8">with weakened gait,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">piercing to death the Yām tree high of base,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">taking the white bark, tasting it with [its] trunk [and] looking up?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
